<DOC><DOCNO> AP891128-0081 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-28-89 1338EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Asia-Refugees     11-28 0305</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Asia-Refugees,0315</SECOND><HEAD>Large Group of Vietnamese Refugees Resettled</HEAD><DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   More than 300 Vietnamese refugees who hadwaited two years in this British colony boarded a plane Tuesday fortheir journey to the West in the largest one-day resettlement ofrefugees from Hong Kong in seven years.   Most of the Vietnamese will go the the United States after sixmonths in the Philippines to study English and learn about life inthe United States.   Others were sent to Sweden and Australia. Government statisticsshowed that was the largest one-day resettlement of Vietnameserefugees in seven years.   Another 12,700 Vietnamese refugees still are waiting in HongKong to be resettled in the West.   More than 5,000 will be resettled in mid-1990, said AlfredKottek, the regional representative of the IntergovernmentalCommittee for Migration who organized the refugees' transportion.   The refugees in Hong Kong either arrived before June 1988 orwere classified as refugees under a screening policy.   In June 1988, the government adopted a policy that treats allVietnamese boat people as illegal immigrants unless they prove theyare fleeing persecution. Those classed as illegal immigrants facerepatriation to their Communist homeland.   Nearly 44,000 Vietnamese boat people in Hong Kong are waiting tobe screened. So far this year, 33,889 have arrived, compared with18,052 in the same period of 1988. Most won't be classified asrefugees.   Francis Maude of the British Foreign Office said forciblerepatriation of Vietnamese boat people from Hong Kong will begin byFebruary or March.   On Thursday, 132 Vietnamese boat people, including 12 babiesborn in Hong Kong, will fly back to their homeland voluntarily, thesixth such group.   Since March, 507 Vietnamese have volunteered to go back under aplan monitored by the United Nations High Commissioner forRefugees, whose office pays each one $50 before departure.</TEXT></DOC>